<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900926-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>900926-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Dandamp;B Alleges 2 Firms,   Ex-Aide, Violated   Database Copyright</HL><DATE>09/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DNB</CO><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Dun andamp; Bradstreet Corp. charged a formeremployee and two Chicago companies with copyrightinfringement and unfair competition in business informationservices.   The business information company, in a lawsuit filed inU.S. District Court in Chicago, charges that InternationalBusiness Lists Inc., Inter-Direct Inc. and Gary E. Walterimproperly copied a database of U.S. businesses and theirexecutives compiled by Dandamp;B and sold it to their customers.</LP><TEXT>   The suit also charges that Mr. Walter breached anagreement not to compete with Dandamp;B for two years after he leftthe company. The suit says Mr. Walter left Dandamp;B around Sept.1, 1988.   Dandamp;B's lawsuit seeks to stop the defendants from marketingthe data, and it asks for unspecified damages. Mr. Walter,president of International Business Lists, called Dandamp;B'scharges &quot;absolutely untrue.&quot; Inter-Direct is the former nameof International Business Lists, he said.</TEXT></DOC>